      <h1 class=3D"with-date title">MongoDB 4.2.6</h1>
   =20
    <div class=3D"sub">
      <div class=3D"author">
        Kyle Kingsbury
      </div>

              <div class=3D"date">2020-05-15</div>
          </div>
  </div>

  <div class=3D"abstract">
    MongoDB is a distributed document database which claims to offer =E2=80=
=9Camong the strongest data consistency, correctness, and safety guarantees=
 of any database available today=E2=80=9D, with =E2=80=9Cfull ACID transact=
ions=E2=80=9D. Jepsen evaluated MongoDB version 4.2.6, and found that even =
at the strongest levels of read and write concern, it failed to preserve sn=
apshot isolation. Instead, Jepsen observed read skew, cyclic information fl=
ow, duplicate writes, and internal consistency violations. Weak defaults me=
ant that transactions could lose writes and allow dirty reads, even downgra=
ding requested safety levels at the database and collection level. Moreover=
, the <code>snapshot</code> read concern did not guarantee snapshot unless =
paired with write concern <code>majority</code>=E2=80=94even for read-only =
transactions. These design choices complicate the safe use of MongoDB trans=
actions. This work was performed independently, without compensation, and c=
onducted in accordance with the <a href=3D"https://jepsen.io/ethics.html">J=
epsen ethics policy</a>. MongoDB, Fauna, and YugaByte, all mentioned in thi=
s report, have previously engaged Jepsen for paid analyses.
  </div>


<article class=3D"section group">
  <div class=3D"col span_12_of_12">
<h1 id=3D"updates"><span class=3D"header-section-number">1</span> Updates</=
h1>
<p><em>2020-05-26: MongoDB identified a <a href=3D"https://jira.mongodb.org=
/browse/SERVER-48307">bug in the transaction retry mechanism</a> which they=
 believe was responsible for the anomalies observed in this report; a patch=
 is scheduled for 4.2.8.</em></p>
<h1 id=3D"background"><span class=3D"header-section-number">2</span> Backgr=
ound</h1>
<p>MongoDB is a popular distributed document database. It offers <a href=3D=
"https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/replication/">replication</a> via a <a hre=
f=3D"https://jepsen.io/analyses/mongodb-3-4-0-rc3#protocol-version-1">homeg=
rown consensus protocol</a> which draws inspiration from <a href=3D"https:/=
/raft.github.io/">Raft</a>, and can distribute data across shards via <a hr=
ef=3D"https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/sharding/">mongos</a>. We previously =
evaluated MongoDB at versions <a href=3D"https://aphyr.com/posts/284-call-m=
e-maybe-mongodb">2.4.3</a>, <a href=3D"https://aphyr.com/posts/322-call-me-=
maybe-mongodb-stale-reads">2.6.7</a>, <a href=3D"https://jepsen.io/analyses=
/mongodb-3-4-0-rc3">3.4.0-rc3</a>, and <a href=3D"https://jepsen.io/analyse=
s/mongodb-3-6-4">3.6.4</a>.</p>
<p>Our most recent report on <a href=3D"https://jepsen.io/analyses/mongodb-=
3-6-4">MongoDB 3.6.4</a> focused on causal consistency and linearizability =
in sharded collections. We found that sharded clusters appeared to offer li=
nearizable reads, writes, and compare-and-set operations against single doc=
uments, so long as users ran with <a href=3D"https://docs.mongodb.com/manua=
l/reference/read-concern/">read concern</a> <code>linearizable</code> and <=
a href=3D"https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/write-concern/">write c=
oncern</a> <code>majority</code>. However, any weaker level of write concer=
n resulted in the loss of committed writes. MongoDB=E2=80=99s default level=
 of write concern was (and remains) acknowledgement by a single node, which=
 means MongoDB may lose data by default. Although the <a href=3D"https://do=
cs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/write-concern/">write concern documentation=
</a> does not make this clear, the <a href=3D"https://docs.mongodb.com/manu=
al/core/replica-set-rollbacks/">rollback documentation</a> states:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>With the default write concern, data may be rolled back if the primary s=
teps down before the write operations have replicated to any of the seconda=
ries.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Similarly, MongoDB=E2=80=99s default level of read concern allows aborte=
d reads: readers can observe state that is not fully committed, and could b=
e discarded in the future. As the <a href=3D"https://docs.mongodb.com/manua=
l/core/read-isolation-consistency-recency/">read isolation consistency docs=
</a> note, =E2=80=9CRead uncommitted is the default isolation level=E2=80=
=9D.</p>
<p>We found that due to these weak defaults, MongoDB=E2=80=99s causal sessi=
ons <a href=3D"https://jepsen.io/analyses/mongodb-3-6-4#discussion">did not=
 preserve causal consistency</a> by default: users needed to specify both w=
rite and read concern <code>majority</code> (or higher) to actually get cau=
sal consistency. MongoDB <a href=3D"https://jira.mongodb.org/browse/SERVER-=
35316?focusedCommentId=3D2008354&amp;page=3Dcom.atlassian.jira.plugin.syste=
m.issuetabpanels%3Acomment-tabpanel#comment-2008354">closed the issue</a>, =
saying it was working as designed, and updated their <a href=3D"https://doc=
s.mongodb.com/manual/core/read-isolation-consistency-recency/#causal-consis=
tency">isolation documentation</a> to note that even though MongoDB offers =
=E2=80=9Ccausal consistency in client sessions=E2=80=9D, that guarantee doe=
s not hold unless users take care to use both read and write concern <code>=
majority</code>. A <a href=3D"https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/core/causal-c=
onsistency-read-write-concerns/">detailed table</a> now shows the propertie=
s offered by weaker read and write concerns.</p>
<p>Curiously, MongoDB omitted any mention of these findings in their <a hre=
f=3D"https://web.archive.org/web/20200508173236/https://www.mongodb.com/jep=
sen">MongoDB and Jepsen</a> page. Instead, that page discusses only passing=
 results, makes no mention of read or write concern, buries the actual repo=
rt in a footnote, and goes on to claim:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>MongoDB offers among the strongest data consistency, correctness, and sa=
fety guarantees of any database available today.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>We encourage MongoDB to report Jepsen findings in context: while MongoDB=
 <em>did</em> appear to offer per-document linearizability and causal consi=
stency with the strongest settings, it also <em>failed</em> to offer those =
properties in most configurations. We think users might want to be aware th=
at their database could lose data by default, but MongoDB=E2=80=99s summary=
 of our work omits any mention of this behavior.</p>
<h2 id=3D"transactional-consistency"><span class=3D"header-section-number">=
2.1</span> Transactional Consistency</h2>
<p>So, does MongoDB offer =E2=80=9Camong the strongest data consistency, co=
rrectness, and safety guarantees=E2=80=9D? Past work suggests that for indi=
vidual document operations, the answer is, =E2=80=9Cyes; MongoDB offers per=
-document linearizability with the strongest settings, but not by default=
=E2=80=9D. However in 2018, MongoDB introduced <em>multi-document transacti=
ons</em>=E2=80=94limited to within a shard=E2=80=94and in 2019, extended th=
ose transactions across shards. What safety properties do these transaction=
s provide?</p>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://www.mongodb.com/">MongoDB home page</a> proudly a=
dvertises =E2=80=9Cfull ACID transactions=E2=80=9D. The <a href=3D"https://=
www.mongodb.com/transactions">transactions page</a> states that MongoDB is =
=E2=80=9Cthe only database that fully combines the power of the document mo=
del and a distributed systems architecture with ACID guarantees,=E2=80=9D a=
 combination also claimed by <a href=3D"https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/az=
ure/cosmos-db/database-transactions-optimistic-concurrency">CosmosDB</a>, <=
a href=3D"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/amazondynamodb/latest/developerguide/=
transaction-apis.html#transaction-isolation">DynamoDB</a>, <a href=3D"https=
://docs.fauna.com/fauna/current/concepts/isolation_levels.html">FaunaDB</a>=
, <a href=3D"https://www.oracle.com/database/nosql-cloud.html">Oracle NoSQL=
</a>, <a href=3D"https://orientdb.com/docs/last/Transactions.html">OrientDB=
</a>, <a href=3D"https://ravendb.net/why-ravendb/acid-transactions">RavenDB=
</a>, <a href=3D"https://help.sap.com/viewer/3e48dd3ad36e41efbdf534a89fdf27=
8f/2.0.04/en-US/b4518419653e44daad99c285039b29c5.html">SAP HANA</a>, <a hre=
f=3D"https://docs.yugabyte.com/latest/architecture/transactions/isolation-l=
evels/">YugaByte DB</a>, et al.</p>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://www.mongodb.com/collateral/mongodb-architecture-g=
uide">MongoDB architecture guide</a> promises ACID transactions =E2=80=9Cma=
intain the same data integrity guarantees you are used to in traditional da=
tabases=E2=80=A6=E2=80=9D, and that MongoDB offers =E2=80=9Cstrong consiste=
ncy by design=E2=80=9D, but offers no more specific claims. The <a href=3D"=
https://www.mongodb.com/collateral/mongodb-multi-document-acid-transactions=
">ACID whitepaper</a> clarifies that MongoDB transactions offer <a href=3D"=
https://jepsen.io/consistency/models/snapshot-isolation">snapshot isolation=
</a>: a reasonably strong model which constitutes the baseline level of con=
sistency for systems like <a href=3D"https://www.postgresql.org/">PostgreSQ=
L</a>. The whitepaper states:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>=E2=80=A6 snapshot read isolation ensures queries and aggregations execu=
ted within a read-only transaction will operate against a globally consiste=
nt snapshot of the database across each primary replica of a sharded cluste=
r.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><a href=3D"https://www.mongodb.com/blog/post/mongodb-multi-document-acid=
-transactions-general-availability">MongoDB</a> <a href=3D"https://www.mong=
odb.com/blog/post/multi-document-transactions-in-mongodb">repeatedly</a> <a=
 href=3D"https://www.mongodb.com/collateral/mongodb-multi-document-acid-tra=
nsactions">summarizes</a> snapshot isolation as =E2=80=9Ctransactions provi=
de a consistent view of data, and enforce all-or-nothing execution to maint=
ain data integrity=E2=80=9D. This is a concise and intuitive summary of sna=
pshot isolation, but we should note that a =E2=80=9Cconsistent view=E2=80=
=9D under snapshot isolation may still be surprising: as Fekete, O=E2=80=99=
Neil, and O=E2=80=99Neil <a href=3D"https://www.cs.umb.edu/~poneil/ROAnom.p=
df">wrote in 2004</a>, read-only transactions can observe nonserializable b=
ehavior under snapshot isolation. Nor does snapshot isolation necessarily m=
aintain data integrity: in their <a href=3D"https://www.microsoft.com/en-us=
/research/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/tr-95-51.pdf">1995 paper defining snap=
shot isolation</a>, Berenson, Bernstein, et al.&nbsp;provided examples of a=
pplications whose integrity constraints could be violated under snapshot is=
olation=E2=80=94for instance, due to write skew.</p>
<h1 id=3D"test-design"><span class=3D"header-section-number">3</span> Test =
Design</h1>
<p>We designed a <a href=3D"https://github.com/jepsen-io/mongodb/tree/83548=
bb8e054170ecc4b8fda70390e40fcca5e30">test suite</a> using the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://github.com/jepsen-io/jepsen">Jepsen</a> distributed systems testing l=
ibrary, and used it to evaluate transactional safety in MongoDB 4.2.6. Our =
tests installed MongoDB=E2=80=99s official Debian packages on clusters of n=
ine Debian 9 nodes. We tested both in LXC and EC2; both exhibited similar b=
ehavior. As per the <a href=3D"https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/tutorial/dep=
loy-shard-cluster/">deployment guidelines</a>, we built <a href=3D"https://=
github.com/jepsen-io/mongodb/blob/83548bb8e054170ecc4b8fda70390e40fcca5e30/=
src/jepsen/mongodb/db.clj#L281-L295">two-shard clusters</a>, with both shar=
ds and the <code>configsvr</code> metadata system running as three-node <a =
href=3D"https://github.com/jepsen-io/mongodb/blob/83548bb8e054170ecc4b8fda7=
0390e40fcca5e30/src/jepsen/mongodb/db.clj#L93-L223">replica sets</a>. All n=
ine nodes ran <a href=3D"https://github.com/jepsen-io/mongodb/blob/83548bb8=
e054170ecc4b8fda70390e40fcca5e30/src/jepsen/mongodb/db.clj#L361-L380">an in=
stance of <code>mongos</code></a>, which serves as the frontend to sharded =
MongoDB clusters.</p>
<p>Our <a href=3D"https://github.com/jepsen-io/mongodb/blob/83548bb8e054170=
ecc4b8fda70390e40fcca5e30/src/jepsen/mongodb/list_append.clj#L74-L136">test=
 workload</a> involved transactions over a rotating pool of documents in a =
single MongoDB collection, each document containing a single array of integ=
ers. Each transaction <a href=3D"https://github.com/jepsen-io/mongodb/blob/=
83548bb8e054170ecc4b8fda70390e40fcca5e30/src/jepsen/mongodb/list_append.clj=
#L52-L72">performed one to four operations</a> over those documents: either=
 reading a single document by primary key <code>_id</code>, or appending (u=
sing <code>$push</code>) a unique integer to a single document=E2=80=99s <c=
ode>value</code> array, again by <code>_id</code>. We <a href=3D"https://gi=
thub.com/jepsen-io/mongodb/blob/83548bb8e054170ecc4b8fda70390e40fcca5e30/sr=
c/jepsen/mongodb/list_append.clj#L84-L98">sharded</a> the collection by <co=
de>_id</code>.</p>
<p>Using <a href=3D"https://github.com/jepsen-io/elle">Elle</a>, a new tran=
saction analysis tool developed in collaboration with UC Santa Cruz=E2=80=
=99s <a href=3D"https://people.ucsc.edu/~palvaro/">Peter Alvaro</a>, Jepsen=
 automatically inferred dependencies between these transactions, and search=
ed for cycles in that graph to identify isolation anomalies. Additional tec=
hniques checked for aborted and intermediate reads, as well as other non-cy=
clic anomalies.</p>
<p>During some of these tests, we introduced <a href=3D"https://github.com/=
jepsen-io/mongodb/blob/83548bb8e054170ecc4b8fda70390e40fcca5e30/src/jepsen/=
mongodb/nemesis.clj">network partitions</a>, targeted to isolate MongoDB pr=
imary nodes.</p>
<h1 id=3D"results"><span class=3D"header-section-number">4</span> Results</=
h1>
<h2 id=3D"sometimes-programs-that-use-transactions-are-worse"><span class=
=3D"header-section-number">4.1</span> Sometimes, Programs That Use Transact=
ions=E2=80=A6 Are Worse</h2>
<p>We began by running our tests without transactions to get a baseline: ea=
ch Jepsen =E2=80=9Ctransaction=E2=80=9D performed only a single read or app=
end operation without using the session or transaction APIs. Since we know =
MongoDB loses updates with any setting less than <code>majority</code>, and=
 exhibits stale reads without read concern <code>linearizable</code>, we se=
t write concern <code>majority</code> and read concern <code>linearizable</=
code> <a href=3D"https://github.com/jepsen-io/mongodb/blob/83548bb8e054170e=
cc4b8fda70390e40fcca5e30/src/jepsen/mongodb/client.clj#L265-L277">on the cl=
ient=E2=80=99s <code>database</code> handle</a>. The resulting histories ap=
peared consistent with snapshot isolation.</p>
<p>We then wrapped those single operations in transactions, and a surprisin=
g behavior appeared: with network partitions, transactions appeared to lose=
 acknowledged writes. For instance, consider <a href=3D"http://jepsen.io.s3=
.amazonaws.com/analyses/mongodb-4.2.6/20200509T083112.000-0400.zip">this hi=
story</a>, where in 30 seconds, updates to eight documents were successfull=
y acknowledged, then disappeared. Here is the history of reads for document=
 555:</p>
<div class=3D"sourceCode" id=3D"cb1"><pre class=3D"sourceCode clj"><code cl=
ass=3D"sourceCode clojure"><a class=3D"sourceLine" id=3D"cb1-1" title=3D"1"=
